04229nam a22006615i 9780691188454DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911884547 a10.1515/97806911884542doi  a(DE-B1597)501624  a(OCoLC)1076420339  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aREL0370002bisacsh04a297.1/2212231 aMadigan, Daniel, eauthor.14aThe Qur'ân's Self-Image :bWriting and Authority in Islam's Scripture /cDaniel Madigan. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4c©2001  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF FIGURES -- tLIST OF TABLES -- tPREFACE -- tA NOTE FOR THE NON-ARABIST -- tTABLE O F ARABIC TRANSLITERATIONS -- tIntroduction -- t1. THE QUR'ÂN AS A BOOK -- t2. THE QUR'ÂN'S REJECTION OF SOME COMMON CONCEPTIONS OF KITÂB -- t3. SEMANTIC ANALYSIS AND THE UNDERSTANDING OF KITÂB -- t4. THE SEMANTIC FIELD OF KITÂB I : VERBAL USES OF THE ROOT K-T-B -- t5. THE SEMANTIC FIELD OF KITÂB II: TITLES AND PROCESSES -- t6. THE SEMANTIC FIELD OF KITÂB III: SYNONYMS AND ATTRIBUTES -- t7. THE ELUSIVENESS OF THE KITÂB: PLURALS, PARTITIVES, AND INDEFINITES -- t8. THE CONTINUING LIFE OF THE KITÂB IN MUSLIM TRADITION -- tAPPENDIX: THE PEOPLE OF TUE KITÂB -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX OF QUR'ÂN QUOTATIONS -- tGENERAL INDEX  aIslam is frequently characterized as a "religion of the book," and yet Muslims take an almost entirely oral approach to their scripture. Qur'ân means "recitation" and refers to the actual words Muslims believe were revealed to Muhammad by God. Many recite the entire sacred text from memory, and it was some years after the Prophet's death that it was first put in book form. Physical books play no part in Islamic ritual. What does the Qur'ân mean, then, when it so often calls itself kitâb, a term usually taken both by Muslims and by Western scholars to mean "book"? To answer this question, Daniel Madigan reevaluates this key term kitâb in close readings of the Qur'ân's own declarations about itself. More than any other canon of scripture the Qur'ân is self-aware. It observes and discusses the process of its own revelation and reception; it asserts its own authority and claims its place within the history of revelation. Here Madigan presents a compelling semantic analysis of its self-awareness, arguing that the Qur'ân understands itself not so much as a completed book, but as an ongoing process of divine "writing" and "re-writing," as God's authoritative response to actual people and circumstances. Grasping this dynamic, responsive dimension of the Qur'ân is central to understanding Islamic religion and identity. Madigan's book will be invaluable not only to Islamicists but also to scholars who study revelation across religious boundaries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 7aRELIGION / Islam / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691188454zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691188454.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN